<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910509-0071</DOCNO><DOCID>910509-0071.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Rolls-Royce PLC:   U.K. Engine Group to Cut   3,000 More Jobs in Division</HL><DATE>05/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11</SO><CO>   U.RR</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><RE>GREAT BRITAIN (UK)</RE><LP>   British engine group Rolls-Royce PLC said it will shed afurther 3,000 jobs across its aerospace division by the endof the year. This is in addition to the 3,000 job cutsalready announced and will reduce the work force in theaerospace unit by the end of 1991 to 28,000.   The cuts will be made at all levels and affect all areas,the company said.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We are suffering from the effects of recession, worsenedby the Gulf war, and by cuts in defense expenditure. . . .Many airlines are in financial difficulty and the relativelyweak dollar is reducing our income,&quot; said Sir Ralph Robbins,chief executive officer.   Sir Ralph said it was &quot;particularly frustrating&quot; that thedefense sector was ailing, especially in light of the factthat its civil aviation side was expected to grow smartlyduring the mid-1990s.   Rolls declared a pay freeze for all employees for the nextsix months, to be followed by a bonus scheme, to beintroduced in January 1992, related to the performance of thebusiness.</TEXT></DOC>